-- Oil Rises, Copper Advances for Third Day: Commodities at Close
-- B y   C h r i s t i a n   S c h m o l l i n g e r
-- 2011-12-22T09:20:54Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-12-22/oil-rises-copper-advances-for-third-day-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI  gauge  of
24 commodities rose 0.3 percent to 642.93 as of 5:09 p.m. in
 Singapore . The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials
advanced 0.3 percent to 1,514.215.  CRUDE OIL  Oil gained for a fourth day in New York after U.S. crude
inventories declined the most in a decade, signaling tighter
supplies in the world’s biggest consumer of the commodity.  Crude for February delivery climbed as much as 72 cents to
$99.39 a barrel in electronic trading on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange  and was $99.31 at 4:18 p.m. Singapore time. The
contract yesterday increased $1.43 to $98.67, the highest close
since Dec. 13. Prices are 8.7 percent higher this year after
climbing 15 percent in 2010.  NATURAL GAS  OIL PRODUCTS  Japan ’s open-specification naphtha forward contracts for
first-half February delivery were bid at $917 a metric ton
against offers at $920 at 12:15 p.m. Singapore time, according
to Ginga Petroleum Singapore Pte , a broker. Yesterday, the
petrochemical feedstock gained for a third day to close at $908.  Naphtha’s premium to London-traded Brent crude futures
decreased 15 cents to $96.36 a ton, based on data compiled by
Bloomberg. This crack spread is a measure of refining profit.  The premium of gasoil, or diesel, to Asian marker Dubai
crude fell 74 cents to $16.89 a barrel, according to PVM Oil
Associates Ltd., a broker. This crack spread is the narrowest
since Oct. 19.  Gasoil swaps for January slid 20 cents, or 0.2 percent, to
$121.70 a barrel, PVM said. Jet fuel’s premium to gasoil was
unchanged for a second day at 40 cents, the lowest since April.
A narrow regrade shows it is less profitable to make  aviation
fuel  over diesel.  January high-sulfur fuel oil swaps increased 25 cents to
$658.50 a ton, according to PVM. Prices advanced for a fourth
day, the longest rising streak since October.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold for immediate delivery traded little-changed at
$1,615.70 an ounce by 8:16 a.m. in  London  after dropping as much
as 0.8 percent earlier. Spot silver fell for a second day,
losing as much as 1.2 percent to $29.045 an ounce. It last
traded at $29.225 an ounce, 5.5 percent lower in 2011.  BASE METALS  Three-month copper rose 0.4 percent to $7,485.75 per metric
ton on the London Metal Exchange at 4:10 p.m. in  Tokyo ,
overturning a loss of 0.8 percent. The price rose 0.6 percent
yesterday and 2.1 percent on Dec. 20. The March-delivery
contract was little changed at $3.398 per pound on the Comex.  Copper for March delivery on the Shanghai Futures Exchange
gained 0.5 percent to close at 54,870 yuan ($8,655) a ton.  GRAINS, OILSEEDS, LIVESTOCK  Corn for March delivery lost as much as 0.5 percent to
$6.135 per bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade and was at $6.15
at 2:12 p.m. in Singapore. It has slipped 2.2 percent this year.
Soybeans for delivery in the same month fell 0.7 percent to
$11.55 a bushel, declining 18 percent this year. Wheat for
delivery in March fell 0.3 percent to $6.15 a bushel, taking the
annual loss to 23 percent.  Wholesale pork slid 3.2 percent to 86.5 cents a pound
yesterday, the lowest since Jan. 24, U.S. Department of
Agriculture data showed yesterday. Hog futures for February
settlement fell 1 percent to settle at 83.275 cents a pound at 1
p.m. on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. The price has climbed
4.4 percent in 2011.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Cotton for March delivery fell 0.3 percent to 86.51 cents a
pound yesterday on ICE Futures U.S. in  New York . The price
dropped 0.3 percent on Dec. 20. The fiber plunged 40 percent
this year amid rising supplies and dwindling demand.  Orange-juice futures for March delivery declined 0.8
percent to $1.6325 a pound. The price dropped 6.6 percent this
month.  Raw sugar for March delivery fell 0.7 percent to settle at
23.32 cents a pound yesterday on ICE Futures U.S. in New York.
The price, up 3.3 percent in the previous three sessions, has
dropped 27 percent in 2011 as demand eased and production rose.  Arabica-coffee futures for March delivery dropped 1.3
percent to $2.199 a pound on ICE.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Christian Schmollinger in Singapore at 
